<F P=100> Sub-Saharan Africa </F>
<H3> <TI>   Congolese President Terms China `Real Friend' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Congolese President Terms China `Real Friend' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1705121894 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0234 
GMT 16 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1705121894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporters Yu Guanmiao (0205 7070 5379) and Wang Yulan </F>
(3769 3768 5695)] 
  [Text] Brazzaville, 15 May (XINHUA) -- Granting an 
interview to XINHUA on the eve of his departure for visit to 
China, Congolese President Pascal Lissouba said China is a real 
friend of Congo with very sincere friendship between the two 
countries. 
  President Lissouba will begin his week-long state visit to 
China on 19 May at the invitation of President Jiang Zemin -- 
his first visit to China. It has been learned that President 
Lissouba will exchange views with Chinese leaders on 
international and bilateral relations during his visit. He will 
also tour other parts of China to better understand conditions 
of its reform, opening up, and construction of a socialist 
market economy. 
  Lissouba is an old friend known to the Chinese people. China 
and Congo established diplomatic ties in 1964 when he was 
premier of Congo. 
  Touching on friendly cooperative relations between China and 
Congo in the past three decades, Lissouba praised such 
cooperation as a model, saying "This kind of cooperation is what 
Congo has been looking for." He maintained that China has been 
consistent in fulfilling its obligations and has done a lot for 
Congo. Lissouba said that he will express respect to the 
Chinese people and their leaders during his forthcoming visit 
and explore jointly with Chinese leaders new ways and means of 
cooperation between the two countries. 
  On Congo's current economic situation, Lissouba said that, 
due to poor management and inappropriate exploitation of state 
resources, Congo is currently heavily indebted with its economy 
on the brink of collapse. He said Congo, with its rich natural 
resources, would like to further strengthen cooperation of 
mutual benefit with China in better opening up and utilizing its 
resources, particularly in promoting agricultural production. 

</TEXT>

