<H4>    Comments on Lhasa Protests </H4>

<F P=102> HK1905133694 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in Chinese 1237 GMT 
19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK1905133694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, 19 May (ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE) -- Chinese 
Foreign Ministry spokesman Wu Jianmin said today that concerned 
authorities in China are putting Wei Jingsheng under house 
surveillance [jian shi ju zhu 4148 6018 1446 0145] and the 
report that he is being indicted is groundless. 
  A reporter asked at today's news conference: It is said that 
Wei Jingsheng will not be re-indicted on treason charges. Will 
he be indicted on other charges? In reply Wu Jianmin made the 
above statement. 
  Another reporter asked: Most recently there have been 
reports that demonstrations and protests had occurred in Lhasa, 
and that some foreigners in Tibet had their passports 
confiscated or were expelled from Tibet. Will you please 
confirm these reports? 
  Wu Jianmin said: I have not heard of such incidents. There 
will not be any problems for foreigners in China as long as they 
obey Chinese law. 
  Wu said: We should be aware that some people are deeply 
prejudiced against China, always attack and spread talk against 
China, and start rumors to confuse people. They do these things 
with ulterior motives. In any case, these words do not merit 
our attention or trust. 

</TEXT>

