<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports U.S. Forces Begin Defense Drill in ROK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Reports U.S. Forces Begin Defense Drill in ROK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1905102194 Beijing XINHUA in English 1012 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1905102194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 19 (XINHUA) -- The United States Forces 
in Korea (USFK) started a three-day defense readiness drill 
involving USFK dependents and American civilians residing in 
South Korea Thursday [19 May], the Korea-U.S. Combined Forces 
Command (CFC) here said. 
  The semi-annual drill, which is called non-combatant 
evacuation operation (neo), will include the checking of 
manpower, paperwork and the operation to evacuate non-combatants 
in the event of war on the Korean peninsula, a CFC spokesman 
said. 
  "The drill is just part of the routine semi-annual program 
having nothing to do with the current situation in which tension 
has escalated due to the standoff involving Pyongyang's nuclear 
weapons program," the spokesman claimed. 
  At present, some 36,000 U.S. troops are stationed in South 
Korea. 

</TEXT>

