<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia Welcomes NATO's `Special Partnership' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia Welcomes NATO's `Special Partnership' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1905171094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1631 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1905171094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, May 19 (XINHUA) -- Russia's government 
officials today reacted positively to NATO's decision to give 
Moscow a "special partnership". 
  Anatoliy Krasikov, President Boris Yeltsin's deputy 
spokesman, said the Russian Government welcomed the "fact that 
Russia's particular features will be taken into account." 
  NATO ambassadors agreed in principle on Wednesday [18 May] 
to 
offer Russia a special relationship, which would reflect its big 
power status. 
  The relationship will be somewhat different from the 
"Partnership for Peace" program, a new form of military 
cooperation between the 16-nation NATO and former Warsaw Pact 
countries. 
  Russia had refused to sign the Partnership for Peace after 
NATO air forces attacked Serbian positions in Bosnia-Herzegovina 
last month. 
  Krasikov hailed NATO's decision Wednesday "a right step," 
arguing that Moscow has never refused to join Partnership for 
Peace. 
  Meanwhile, Foreign Ministry Spokesman Grigoriy Karasin said, 
"The reports coming from Brussels show the proposal is of great 
importance, and its tone sounds generally positive to us." 
  The North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) wants to build 
an informal relationship of intense contacts with Russia on 
issues like Bosnia, peacekeeping and nuclear arms without giving 
Moscow the right to consultation on security questions. 
  NATO's decision came one week before Russian Defense 
Minister 
Pavel Grachev is to visit NATO headquarters in Brussels next 
Tuesday to outline Russia's views on "Partnership for Peace." 
  Eighteen countries have so far signed the "Partnership for 
Peace," a program regarded by most of former Warsaw Pact nations 
as the first step towards full NATO membership. 

</TEXT>

