<H3> <TI>   U.S. Official Cited on NATO Meeting Regarding Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Official Cited on NATO Meeting Regarding Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2005050694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0440 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2005050694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, May 19 (XINHUA) -- When defense 
ministers of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) meet 
in Brussels next week, NATO's ties with Russia will be at the 
top of the agenda. 
  A senior U.S. Administration official, briefing reporters 
today on the background to the meeting, said the 16-member 
organization will judge whether Russian Defense Minister Pavel 
Grachev's tone is "conciliatory or confrontational" when he 
makes a presentation on Moscow's military doctrine. 
  U.S. Defense Secretary William Perry is planning a meeting 
with Grachev, the official said. 
  The official refuted press suggestions that NATO was 
offering 
a "special partnership" to Russia, but said the organization 
would recognize "Russia's strategic weight and interest in 
European affairs." 
  Russia had agreed to join NATO's "Partnership for Peace" 
earlier but postponed the move following NATO's threats to bomb 
the Bosnian Serbs. 
  The official said he was "hopeful" that Russia would still 
join, although Moscow may choose to have Foreign Minister Andrey 
Kozyrev sign the agreement later when he attends a North 
Atlantic Council meeting in Istanbul, Turkey, in early June. 
  Also attending next week's meeting will be officials from 
the 
18 countries that have already joined NATO's "Partnership for 
Peace." 
  Besides the partnership, NATO officials will also be 
discussing the Bosnian crisis and the nuclear issue on the 
Korean peninsula, the official said. 

</TEXT>

