<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK Expresses Concern Over DPRK's Reactor Rod Discharge </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ROK Expresses Concern Over DPRK's Reactor Rod Discharge </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2005103694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0945 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2005103694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 20 (XINHUA) -- South Korea expressed 
concern Friday [20 May] over reports that the International 
Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) team conducting inspection in the 
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) confirmed Pyongyang 
has already begun withdrawing spent fuel rods from its 
5-megawatt nuclear reactor. 
  "We express regret and concern over the IAEA inspection team 
confirming that North Korea has started replacing spent fuel 
rods at the 5-megawatt reactor on its own," Foreign Ministry 
Spokesman Chang Ki-ho said here. 
  The DPRK notified the United States and the IAEA 
respectively 
earlier that it could no longer defer removal of the nuclear 
fuel rods from its reactor due to technical reasons. 
  Chang said that the South Korean Government will await the 
results of negotiations between the DPRK and the IAEA, then 
discuss the necessary safety steps after refueling and consult 
closely with its allies on follow-up measures. 
  "The government is paying heed to the IAEA announcement that 
there is still room for safety measures if North Korea stops 
withdrawing at this stage," he noted. 
  The IAEA inspection team said that the DPRK is still in the 
early stage of replacing spent fuel rods. 
  As the IAEA has proposed sending delegates to discuss 
safeguards needed in the refueling process for safety reasons, 
South Korea is asking the DPRK to abide by nuclear safeguards 
after immediate talks with the IAEA, Chang said. 
  Meanwhile, South Korea decided Friday to consider asking the 
United Nations Security Council to take additional action if the 
DPRK rejects the IAEA's proposal to suspend the changing of fuel 
rods at its reactor and permit complete inspection. 
  The decision was made at a unification and security policy 
coordination meeting attended by Yi Hong-ku, deputy prime 
minister and national unification board minister, and other 
related ministers. 

</TEXT>

