<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-098 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> West Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Ruihuan Continues Visit to European Countries </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Li Ruihuan Continues Visit to European Countries </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Urges EU Abolish Trade Restrictions </H4>

<F P=102> OW1905163894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1559 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1905163894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, May 18 (XINHUA) -- The European Union (EU) 
should abolish trade restrictions on China, urged Li Ruihuan, 
chairman of the National Committee of the Chinese People's 
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC). 
  Li made the call when meeting here today with Willy Claes, 
Belgian deputy prime minister and minister of foreign affairs, 
on Sino-European and Belgian relations. 
  The European Union (EU) still has some restrictions on 
Sino-European relations which is incompatible with present 
needs, Li said, these restrictions should be abolished. 
  Li expressed Chinese belief that Sino-European relations 
would develop smoothly if the two sides carry out the principles 
of seeking common ground while reserving differences, 
respecting, non-interference of each other's internal affairs 
and peaceful mutual benefit. 
  Showing his understanding on Li's viewpoint, Claes said that 
the EU should adopt a positive attitude towards China, relaxing 
its restrictions to China on trade and economy and opening to 
the country. 
  Li also said that the Chinese Government attaches importance 
in developing long-standing, equal and mutually beneficial 
relations with West European countries and that those relations 
are good on the whole. 
  He stressed that both sides share the same or similar views 
on essential international affairs, the economic base for 
cooperation is concrete and the future for development is 
tremendous. 
  Chairman Li said that Sino-Belgian trade and economic 
relations have been increasing in recent years. 
  The healthy and fast pace of China's national economy with 
its big market and advanced technology, equipment and funds from 
Belgium offers great cooperation potential and a bright future 
for trade and economic cooperation of the two countries, he 
added. 
  Li expressed China's willingness in making joint efforts 
with 
Belgian parties to promote mutually-beneficial cooperation 
between the two countries. 
  Claes said the trade and economic cooperation between 
Belgium 
and China are satisfactory and Belgium has a strong wish to 
develop more relations with China. 
  He added, Belgium will take new measures to expand trade and 
economic exchanges with the country and I believe the chairman's 
visit will influence positively the understanding and 
cooperations between Belgium and China. 
  Freddy Thilemans, the mayor of Brussels, hosted a welcome 
ceremony this afternoon for Chairman Li, who is on the last leg 
of a five-nation European tour, which has already taken him to 
Finland, Sweden, Norway and Denmark. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-50668 </DOCNO>
