<F P=100> West Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Ruihuan Continues Visit to European Countries </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Li Ruihuan Continues Visit to European Countries </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Meets With Belgian Premier Dehaene </H4>

<F P=102> OW2005040894 Beijing XINHUA in English 0302 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2005040894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, May 19 (XINHUA) -- China hopes to develop 
long-term and stable cooperative relations with other countries 
and learn from their strong points, a senior Chinese official 
said here today. 
  Li Ruihuan, chairman of the National Committee of the 
Chinese 
People's Political Consultative Conference, said this while 
meeting with Belgian Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene here. 
  The two leaders praised the successful cooperation between 
China and Belgium in economy and trade and hoped for a long-term 
and stable development of their friendly ties. 
  Li said that his Europe tour sought to learn from other 
states their experiences which will benefit China. China's 
cooperation with the outside world would promote both its own 
modernization and global peace and development as well, he added. 
  He said China was far behind the Western countries in 
economy 
and science as it had to spend time and energy over the past 
century winning national liberation from the imperialist 
aggression. 
  Starting to open itself to the world and the international 
market in the 1980s, he said, China had been drawing on the 
experiences of other countries, accelerating its development and 
contributing to the international community. 
  The Belgian prime minister, meanwhile, hailed the friendship 
between the two countries, noting that the exchange of 
high-level visits had increased in recent years and Belgium had 
made more and more investment in China. 
  He predicted that China's rapid economic growth would have a 
significant influence upon Asia. 
  Dehaene added that his country pays great attention to and 
appreciates China's constructive role in the United Nations 
Security Council. 
  He also expressed confidence that Li's visit would promote 
Sino- Belgian ties in the political and economic fields. 
  The Chinese official arrived here Tuesday [17 May] for a 
five- day visit to Belgium, the last leg of his 
five-European-nation tour. 

</TEXT>

