<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shanghai's Private Economy Booms </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shanghai's Private Economy Booms </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2005093994 Beijing XINHUA in English 0925 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2005093994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, May 20 (XINHUA) -- The private economy is 
booming in Shanghai, China's largest economic center. 
  According to the latest statistics, the city now has about 
10,000 private enterprises with a registered capital of 2.6 
billion yuan, increases of 14 percent and 50 percent, 
respectively, over 1993. 
  China's private economy disappeared in the 1950's, but 
resumed and burgeoned after 1979, when China began its national 
reform and opening to the outside world. 
  To help the private economy develop healthily, the municipal 
government has worked out a package of policies in favor of 
private businesses. 
  Encouraged by the municipal government, more and more 
scientists have left their research institutions to set up 
non-governmental enterprises specializing in spreading research 
findings, and Chinese scholars studying abroad are retuning to 
Shanghai to set up businesses. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

