<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shenzhen Electronics Industry Leads Beijing, Shanghai </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shenzhen Electronics Industry Leads Beijing, Shanghai </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK1905145194 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 1342 GMT 
19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK1905145194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shenzhen, May 19 (CNS) -- The electronic industry 
in Shenzhen, the Special Economic Zone city in Guangdong 
Province, takes a lead both in its production value and export 
value among big cities including Beijing and Shanghai in the 
country. 
  According to the Shenzhen Electronic Industry Association, 
the city saw its electronic industrial output value of RMB 
[renminbi] 18 billion last year, making up 12.9 percent of the 
total value earned from this sector in the country. The export 
value of this industry was nearly RMB 10.8 billion, accounting 
for 15.3 percent of the total value of this kind of products in 
the country. 
  There are to date over 1,500 enterprises specializing in 
this 
industry in the city with employment of 160,000 people. The 
city has seen its dozen of products including colour TV sets, 
video cassette recorders, mini computers, program-controlled 
switchboards, telephones, colour tubes, discs, liquid crystal 
indicators and software ranking first in the country in terms of 
their production volume, and some of them have entered the 
international market. 
  China's annual capacity of production of discs has to date 
reached 1.5 billion, about one fourth of the total turned out in 
the world. 800 million of them were produced in the city. 
  39 out of 55 new- and high-tech enterprises confirmed in the 
city are electronic ones and a number of high-tech items 
including production lines of computers and laser devices, super 
large-scale integrated circuits, mobile phones and magnetic 
heads for video cassette recorders have been put into operation 
or under construction. They will greatly promote the 
development of the electronic industry in the city. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

