<H3> <TI>   Economics Minister Reportedly Invited to APEC </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Economics Minister Reportedly Invited to APEC </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2005084794 Taipei CNA in English 0829 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2005084794 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By P.C. Wu and Debbie Kuo] </F>
  [Text] Bali, Indonesia, May 19 (CNA) -- Republic of China 
[ROC]'s Economic Affairs Minister P.K. Chiang has been invited 
to take part in a ministerial meeting of the Asia-Pacific 
Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum scheduled for Oct. 6 in 
Jakarta. 
  According to APEC sources, Indonesian Trade Minister Satrio 
Joedono sent invitations Thursday to trade and economics 
ministers of all 17 APEC member nations, including the Republic 
of China. 
  The time and place of the October APEC ministerial meeting 
was decided Thursday during an APEC senior officials meeting, 
the second of its kind, which opened Wednesday here with more 
than 100 delegates from 17 nations and regions taking part. 
  Other decisions made by the senior officials Thursday 
included that the third and fourth APEC senior officials 
meetings will be held Sept. 10-14 in Yogjakarta in central Java 
and Nov. 6-10 in Jakarta, respectively. 
  Indonesia is the chair country for 1994 APEC meetings and 
activities. 
  The APEC senior officials also decided that APEC ministers 
will meet in Jakarta for another round of talks Nov. 11-12 after 
the October meeting. 
  The APEC leadership meeting is scheduled for Nov. 15 in 
Bogor 
in western Java, the senior officials decided. 
  The APEC senior officials Thursday focused their discussions 
on the development of manpower resources, promotion of small and 
medium-sized enterprises and infrastructure development. 
  The three-day meeting will also discuss follow-up plans for 
last year's APEC leadership meeting in Seattle. 
  Taipei is represented by an 18-member delegation led by Shen 
Kuo-hsiung, director of the Foreign Affairs Ministry's 
Department of International Organizations. 
  APEC groups 17 nations, and Chile is expected to become the 
18th member by the end of this year. An additional 14 nations 
have expressed interest in joining the club. 

</TEXT>

