<H3> <TI>   Businessmen Endorse Holding Company Trade Project </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Businessmen Endorse Holding Company Trade Project </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1605140394 Taipei CNA in English 1329 GMT 16 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1605140394 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Flor Wang] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 16 (CNA) -- Acting to respond to the 
government's efforts to correct the nation's chronic towering 
trade deficit with Japan, business figures on Monday [16 May] 
echoed and endorsed a government plan to set up a privately 
owned holding company. 
  At a meeting with Board of Foreign Trade officials and 
private sector representatives Monday, Kao Ching-yuan, chairman 
of the Chinese National Federation of Industries, gave his 
backing to the proposed company, and suggested that the 
government finance the company's research and development 
projects after its establishment. 
  A follow-up meeting scheduled for June 9 by the Ministry of 
Economic Affairs is set to make further plans regarding the 
company's proposed opening date and what products it will make 
in trying to replace Japanese imports, the board said. 
  The board said the holding company would first begin 
producing key parts and components that are imported from Japan 
to the tune of US$50 million each on a yearly basis. 
  Taiwan posted a trade surplus of US$4.96 billion in the 
first 
four months of the year, up 4.5 percent from the same period 
last year. But its deficit with Japan was US$14.22 billion last 
year, and the figure is expected to hit US$15.5 billion this 
year. 

</TEXT>

