<H3> <TI>   Central Bank Not Adjusting Key Interest Rate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Central Bank Not Adjusting Key Interest Rate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1905140794 Taipei CNA in English 1338 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1905140794 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Bear Li] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 19 (CNA) -- The Central Bank of China 
on Thursday [19 May] decided not to adjust the local rediscount 
rate and the New Taiwan [NT] dollar's exchange rate against the 
U.S. currency. 
  The Central Bank reached the decision in a meeting of its 
board of directors and supervisors. 
  The bank said it is unnecessary for Taiwan to follow the 
example of the United States and raise its rediscount rate, or 
the interest rate the central bank charges banks, because 
Taiwan's m2 money supply growth rate was still high at over 15.2 
percent in April, leaving room for commodity prices to move up. 
  Taiwan's current rediscount rate was 5.5 percent. 
  In addition, it said, the new Taiwan dollar's exchange rate 
was at a "reasonable" level against the greenback. The U.S. 
dollar finished Thursday on the Taiwan foreign exchange at 
NT$26.84. 
  Observers said the central bank's decision to maintain a 
loose monetary policy is in line with its policy to revitalize 
the stagnant economy and export growth. 

</TEXT>

