<H3> <TI>   Reports on Foreign Ministry News Conference Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reports on Foreign Ministry News Conference Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Denies `Jamming' of VOA Broadcasts </H4>

<F P=102> HK1905140794 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in Chinese 1238 GMT 
19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK1905140794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, 19 May (ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE) -- Chinese 
Foreign Ministry spokesman Wu Jianmin said today that there is 
no such thing as jamming of the Voice of America. 
  At today's press conference, a ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE reporter 
asked: According to a NEW YORK TIMES report, a senior U.S. 
official who accompanied Christopher on his visit to the Middle 
East said that China had agreed with the U.S. side on sending 
technicians to discuss measures to stop the jamming of VOA. The 
report says that this is another major concession made by China 
to win the MFN renewal. Could you please confirm this? 
  Wu Jianmin replied that the Chinese side has agreed with the 
United States to send technicians to China to talk about 
technical matters, such as the question of overlapping 
frequencies. The study of the technical problem of broadcasting 
frequency overlapping by the experts from the two sides has 
nothing to do with the most-favored-nation trading status. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

