<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Dismissal of Hong Kong Affairs Adviser </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reaction to Dismissal of Hong Kong Affairs Adviser </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    State Council Spokesman Explains </H4>

<F P=102> HK1905140594 Hong Kong ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in Chinese 1113 
GMT 19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK1905140594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, 19 May (ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE)--A spokesman 
from the State Council's Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office 
spoke about the dismissal of Mr. Anthony Cheung Bing-leung from 
the post of Hong Kong affairs adviser. 
  The spokesman said: All of the Hong Kong affairs advisers 
jointly recruited by the State Council Hong Kong and Macao 
Affairs Office and XINHUA Hong Kong Branch are appointed in a 
personal capacity, but party representatives will never be 
invited to take up such posts. This point was repeatedly stated 
when the Hong Kong Affairs advisers were appointed. However, 
after accepting his appointment as a Hong Kong affairs adviser, 
Mr. Cheung claimed that if the "Democratic Party" Central 
Committee decided that there was no need for someone to act as a 
Hong Kong affairs adviser and that person must resign, he would 
follow the decision. This violates our above-mentioned 
principle of recruiting Hong Kong affairs advisers and is thus 
unacceptable. 
  The spokesman also said: In the future, Mr. Cheung is still 
welcome to give us, in a personal capacity, useful and 
constructive advice about Hong Kong's prosperity and stability 
and a smooth transition. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

