<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Qiao Shi Suggests Use for Surplus Rural Labor </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Qiao Shi Suggests Use for Surplus Rural Labor </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1905134294 Beijing XINHUA in English 1330 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1905134294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tianjin, May 19 (XINHUA) -- Qiao Shi, a top Chinese 
leader, this week suggested that surplus rural labor should be 
organized to build roads and water conservancy facilities. 
  He made the suggestion while on tour of the north China port 
city of Tianjin from May 15-18. Qiao, chairman of the Standing 
Committee of the National People's Congress, visited a number of 
factories, a duck farm and a TV transmission tower in Tianjin. 
  During his tour he said that the expansion of township-run 
enterprises and the construction of small cities will change the 
face of China's countryside and absorb surplus labor effectively 
as well. 
  He told local officials that as long as Tianjin tries to 
deepen reforms and open wider to the rest of the world, it will 
certainly achieve greater development and promote opening up and 
economic growth in the whole of north China. 
  Qiao, who is also a standing committee member of the 
Political Bureau of the Chinese Communist Party Central 
Committee, praised the Tianjin municipal leaders for paying 
close attention to intensifying enterprise restructuring. 
  The invigoration of major state-owned enterprise makes it 
imperative to guide them in orienting themselves with the market 
and improve their economic returns, he noted. 
  These enterprises should be encouraged to import 
sophisticated technology and managerial expertise so as to 
improve their production processes, the quality of their 
products and their management, he said. 
  Moreover, it is necessary to promote vocational training in 
various forms among workers, and relieve enterprises' financial 
burdens by introducing a social security system in order to 
create a good environment for these enterprises to develop, he 
added. 

</TEXT>

