<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Official Rules Out U.S. Visit by Li </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Official Rules Out U.S. Visit by Li </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2005065094 Taipei China Broadcasting Corporation News 
Network in Mandarin 2300 GMT 19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2005065094 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei China Broadcasting Corporation News 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Mandarin </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Hookup" program] </F>
  [Text] In response to an invitation to visit the U.S. 
extended to President Li Teng-hui jointly by Republican Senator 
Murkowski and Senator Brown, an official of the Ministry of 
Foreign Affairs said: During past years, many U.S. senators and 
congressmen as well as academic organizations have invited 
President Li to visit the United States. But under the U.S. 
system in which administrative, legislative, and judicial 
functions are separate, President Li's visit to the United 
States is possible only when, in addition to the maneuvering on 
the part of Congress, the administrative branch should have good 
will. Given the current policy of the United States, which 
deems mutual visits by high-level officials not in line with its 
interests, President Li's visit to the United States is 
impossible. 
  However, the official said: If there are more voices of 
support, this will put pressure on the U.S. Government. The 
accumulation of such efforts will certainly bloom and produce 
fruits. A case in point is the U.S. arms sales to us. We have 
worked hard on this issue over the past 13 years. Another 
example is our entry to GATT. In the future, we will mobilize 
more people to support us. It is our hope that the U.S. side 
will come to understand that we do not mean to sabotage the 
relations between the United States and Communist China. It is 
hoped that the United States will separately deal with its ties 
with Communist China and its ties with us. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

