<H3> <TI>   Russia Approves NATO's `Special Partnership' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia Approves NATO's `Special Partnership' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2105154794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1446 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2105154794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, May 21 (XINHUA) -- Russia said on Friday [20 
May] that it has approved a new partnership deal with NATO that 
would take into account Russia's special status. 
  The ITAR-TASS News Agency quoted Russian Defense Minister 
Pavel Grachev as saying that Russia would join the "Partnership 
for Peace" program NATO has offered former Soviet Republics only 
if NATO approves Russia's proposals. 
  The approval came after the 16-member NATO offered a 
"special 
partnership" to Russia on Wednesday to encourage the country to 
join its "partnership for peace" program. 
  "Russia is interested in a more serious and substantive form 
of relations with NATO than envisaged by the Partnership for 
Peace program," said Grachev, who is due to visit NATO next week. 
  Russia has insisted that the "Partnership for Peace" does 
not 
offer Russia the status it deserves as a big nuclear power. 
  Reports quoted President Boris Yeltsin as saying NATO may 
acknowledge Russia's special status in a protocol within the 
framework of the "partnership for peace" or in a separate 
bilateral document. 
  Grachev said he intends to submit Russia's new vision of 
European security at next Tuesday's meeting of NATO and former 
Warsaw Pact defense ministers in Brussels. 
  According to ITAR-TASS, Grachev will also make a report on 
provisions of Russia's military doctrine, which was approved in 
November 1993. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

