<F P=100> Central Eurasia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Second Trade Meeting With Russia To Be Held in Beijing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Second Trade Meeting With Russia To Be Held in Beijing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2205133394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1304 GMT 22 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2205133394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, May 22 (XINHUA) -- China and Russia are to 
hold the second meeting of the Sino-Russian Committee on 
Economic, Trade, Scientific and Technological Cooperation here 
from Tuesday [24 May] to Thursday. 
  The two sides will exchange opinions on furthering bilateral 
cooperation in the four areas. 
  Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing and Russian Deputy Prime 
Minister Aleksandr Shokhin will co-chair the meeting. 
  China and Russia are neighbors highly complementary to each 
other in terms of economy and enjoy economic and trade 
cooperation in many fields, according to Geng Xuncai, deputy 
director of the European Affairs Department of China's Ministry 
of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC). 
  He said that bilateral economic and trade ties are 
developing 
rapidly, with last year's trade volume reaching 7.7 billion U.S. 
dollars, an increase of 31 percent over 1992. 
  In addition, means of bilateral economic and trade are 
diversifying with the development of barter trade, cash trade, 
compensation trade, entrepot trade, leasing, project engineering 
and labor services. 
  He said that the Chinese Government maintains an active 
attitude towards the development of Sino-Russian trade and such 
cooperation has a bright prospect. 
  In general trade, using its main foreign trade channels such 
as large trade corporations, the Chinese side will seize the 
opportunity to press for a gradual shift from the dominant 
barter trade to cash trade with involvement of all foreign trade 
means. 
  He said that the Chinese side will continue to stress the 
role of border and regional economic and trade cooperation, 
further strengthening administration over such cooperation and 
the standardization of commodities inspection, in a bid to 
better facilitate the development of such cooperation and 
two-way investment. 
  In scientific and technological cooperation, he said that 
China hopes for extending cooperation to such high-tech fields 
as aviation, space technology, medical sciences, chemical 
industry and machine-building. 
  He added that the problem of communications constitutes an 
obstacle in bilateral trade, hoping that the two countries will 
make full use of land transportation, along with the proper 
development of sea transportation. 
  He said that he believes the coming meeting will accelerate 
the development of bilateral economic and trade cooperation. 

</TEXT>

