<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Southeast Asia &amp; Pacific </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sihanouk To Meet Khieu Samphan in Beijing 25 May </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sihanouk To Meet Khieu Samphan in Beijing 25 May </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2205130394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1240 GMT 22 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2205130394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Phnom Penh, May 22 (XINHUA) -- King Norodom 
Sihanouk of Cambodia will meet Khmer Rouge leader Khieu Samphan 
on May 25 in Beijing, the Khmer Rouge -- or Democratic Kampuchea 
-- representative office here said today. 
  Khieu, who will be attending a round-table meeting on 
Cambodia in Pyongyang from May 27 to 30, will fly to Beijing on 
May 25 to attend a dinner hosted by Sihanouk, said a spokesman 
for the office, who added that Khieu had thanked Sihanouk for 
the invitation. 
  Meanwhile, Sihanouk today urged the four participants in the 
round-table meeting in Pyongyang to agree upon an unconditional 
and immediate ceasefire and to pledge their commitment to unity. 
  In a letter to the participants sent from his residence in 
Beijing, Sihanouk said that he is not trying to "impose a 
political solution to the bloody and tragic `problem' existing 
between the Royal Government of Cambodia and the Democratic 
Kampuchea Party." 
  "I would like to implore you to accept, while in short of a 
political solution, an unconditional, immediate, total and 
irreversible ceasefire across Cambodia," said Sihanouk. 
  He suggested that the ceasefire be supervised by an 
inter-Cambodian commission of control, to be formed of a number 
of army officers from both sides of the conflict, and headed by 
two neutral generals representing Sihanouk himself -- General 
Oum Mannorine and General Buor Holl. 
  He also called on the participants in the round-table 
meeting 
to sign a declaration pledging themselves to national unity, 
territorial integrity based on the 1963-69 border, and "our 
national ideals of peace, national unity and progress." 
  "We will continue to do all we can to find a peaceful and 
political solution to the 'problem' which still divides the 
Royal Government of Cambodia and the Democratic Kampuchea 
Party," said Sihanouk. 
  The four participants in the round table meeting will be 
Chea 
Sim, president of the Cambodian National Assembly, Norodom 
Ranariddh and Hun Sen, the two co-prime ministers of the royal 
government, and Khieu Samphan, president of the Democratic 
Kampuchea Party, or the Khmer Rouge. 

</TEXT>

