<H3> <TI>   Shanghai's Foreign Exchange Market Increases Turnover </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shanghai's Foreign Exchange Market Increases Turnover </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2305074194 Beijing XINHUA in English 0717 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2305074194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, May 23 (XINHUA) -- The individual trading 
of foreign exchange has become a favorite investment business 
among residents in China's largest economic center. 
  According to the latest statistics, a total of 15,000 deals 
involving 100 million U.S. dollars have been concluded since 
last December, when the Shanghai branches of the Bank of China 
and the communications bank started such business. 
  At present, individuals with foreign currency in hand may 
exchange it according to the rates on the international foreign 
exchange market. 
  Until late last year all privately owned foreign exchange 
had 
to be deposited in banks. 
  Wang Qinpei, an official of the Shanghai branch of the 
Communications Bank, said that the individual savings deposits 
in foreign exchange in banks in Shanghai had risen from less 
than 100 million U.S. dollars in 1987 to 2.4 billion U.S. 
dollars by the end of last year, accounting for about one fifth 
of the country's total private foreign exchange savings deposits. 

</TEXT>

