<H3> <TI>   Shenzhen Becomes Nation's Leading Electronics Exporter </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shenzhen Becomes Nation's Leading Electronics Exporter </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2205025494 Beijing XINHUA in English 0147 GMT 22 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2205025494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shenzhen, May 22 (XINHUA) -- The Shenzhen Special 
Economic Zone (SEZ) in south China has overtaken Shanghai, the 
traditional electronics producer, and Beijing to become the 
leading producer and exporter, according to Wang Dianfu, 
chairman of the Shenzhen Electronics Trade Association. 
  Wang, who used to head China's National Electronics 
Corporation before the present Ministry of Electronics was 
reestablished in 1993, said that 60 percent of Shenzhen's 
electronics products are sold outside China, leading the rest of 
the country, 
  He said there are 1,500 electronics enterprises in the SEZ, 
producing 18 billion yuan (about two billion U.S. dollars) in 
annual output value. With 160,000 employees, the electronics 
industry in the city made 10.8 billion yuan (1.2 billion U.S. 
dollars) in output value, he said. 
  Most of Shenzhen's electronics enterprises are 
trans-provincial enterprise groups such as Konka, Huaqiang-Sony, 
Hitachi, heading China in the production of such products as 
colour TVs, tape recorders, microcomputers, telephone 
switchboards and software. 
  Among Shenzhen's 55 hi-tech enterprises, 39 are in the 
electronics industry, the expert said. A number of hi-tech 
electronics enterprises are being constructed in the city, with 
more shares in components and appliance related products. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

