<H3> <TI>   Taipower Announces Nuclear Waste Agreement With Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Taipower Announces Nuclear Waste Agreement With Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Letter of Intent May Be Signed </H4>

<F P=102> OW2105075694 Taipei CNA in English 0734 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2105075694 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Sofia Wu] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 21 (CNA) -- Taiwan and Russia may 
cooperate in nuclear waste research and disposal, a Taiwan power 
company (Taipower) spokesman said Saturday [21 May]. 
  Taipower may commission Russia to dispose of high-level 
radioactive waste, the spokesman said. 
  Taipower Chairman Chang Chung-chien visited Moscow earlier 
this week at the invitation of the Russian Academy of Science to 
inspect its nuclear energy research facilities. 
  Chang has reached consensus with Russian academy officials 
on 
cooperation in high-level nuclear waste research and treatment, 
the spokesman said. 
  "The two sides may sign a letter of intent in the near 
future 
confirming their willingness to cooperate in nuclear waste 
disposal," the spokesman said. 
  In addition to waste treatment, the two sides may [words 
indistinct] operation to the study of radioactive substances and 
technology for high-level nuclear waste disposal. 
  The Russian academy is expected to draft a definitive 
framework for bilateral cooperation in these fields in the near 
future, the spokesman noted. 
  To test Russia's treatment technology and determine 
transport 
routes, Taipower may first send a batch of medium-level nuclear 
waste to Russia for disposal, the spokesman said. 
  "We'll make sure that the cooperative project is carried out 
without violating any international regulations or causing 
unnecessary environmental disputes," he added. 
  Chang left Moscow Friday for Norway where he will attend an 
international energy resources development seminar. 

</TEXT>

