<H3> <TI>   Export-Import Bank To Open Office in Vietnam </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Export-Import Bank To Open Office in Vietnam </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2105083994 Taipei CNA in English 0713 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2105083994 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Y.C. Tsai] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 21 (CNA) -- The state-run Export-Import 
Bank of the Republic of China [ROC] is planning to open a 
reprsentative office in Vietnam as part of its efforts to help 
promote the government's "southern strategy," a spokesman for 
the bank said Saturday [21 May]. 
  The strategy encourages Taiwan manufacturers to increase 
investment in Southeast Asia. 
  If all goes well, the spokesman pointed out, the Vietnamese 
office will be the bank's second such office in Asia. The bank 
established an office in Jakarta, Indonesia in 1990. 
  The bank, which renders services in overseas investment 
credit and insurance as well as medium and long-term 
export-import loans, will be able to give a helping hand to 
Taiwan investors intending to go to Vietnam, he elaborated. 
  Taiwan was the largest foreign investor in Vietnam at the 
end 
of 1993 with 117 investment projects totaling U.S.$1.53 billion. 
  Currently, only two Taiwan financial institutions maintain 
offices in the Indochinese country. The International 
Commercial Bank of China has a representative office in Ho Chi 
Minh City and the Cathay Investment and Trust Co., Ltd. 
maintains a branch in Hanoi. 
  The spokesman stressed that the export-import bank is 
willing 
to help pioneer Taiwan's overseas markets. 
  To help achieve the goal, he said, the bank opened offices 
in 
Mexico City, Mexico and Budapest, Hungary last year. 

</TEXT>

