<H3> <TI>   Taipei To Help Automate Vietnamese Agriculture </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Taipei To Help Automate Vietnamese Agriculture </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2305090494 Taipei CNA in English 0809 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2305090494 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Debbie Kuo] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 23 (CNA) -- The Republic of China is 
considering loaning an additional U.S.$5 million to Vietnam to 
help the Indochinese country automate its agricultural industry, 
the Ministry of Economic Affairs reported Monday [23 May]. 
  To initiate the plan, Taiwan may establish a holding company 
in Vietnam which will provide the Vietnamese agricultural sector 
with farm machines, technical consultation, and after-sale 
services. 
  In addition, the Council of Agriculture is also studying the 
feasibility of sending agricultural experts to Vietnam to help 
out in forestation and forest conservation. 
  The proposed loan will be offered by the ministry's 
International Economic Cooperation and Development Fund (IECDF) 
established in 1989 to provide financial aid to needy developing 
countries. 
  During the past two years, IECDF has lent U.S.$30 million to 
Vietnam to expand a highway, U.S.$15 million to fund the 
development of small and medium-sized Vietnamese companies, and 
U.S.$10 million for the development of an industrial park to 
house Taiwan-invested factories. 
  According to Vietnamese Government tallies, Taiwan remains 
the top foreign investor in Vietnam, channeling U.S.$1.567 
billion into the country for 123 investment projects as of March 
28. 
  In 1993 alone, Taiwan investments in Vietnam totaled 
U.S.$388 
million, the second highest among foreign investors behind Hong 
Kong which sent U.S.$607 million in Vietnam, the tallies showed. 
Most Taiwan investments focused on footwear processing, food 
processing, textile, wood processing, construction, and 
construction material industries. 

</TEXT>

