<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economics Ministry Reports Export Orders Up in Apr </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Economics Ministry Reports Export Orders Up in Apr </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2105083894 Taipei CNA in English 0729 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2105083894 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Sofia Wu] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 21 (CNA) -- Export orders received by 
Taiwan manufacturers amounted to U.S.$7.8 billion in April, up 
9.03 percent from the year-earlier level, the Ministry of 
Economic Affairs reported Saturday [21 May]. 
  But, compared with March, export orders declined by U.S.$11 
million, the ministry said. 
  Orders for telecommunications and information processing 
equipment, metal products and textiles increased in April, but 
purchase contracts for plastic and rubber products, electric 
appliances and transport equipment dropped. 
  Hong Kong remained the largest source of export orders, up 
12.74 percent from March. Compared with last April, orders from 
the British colony, a conduit for indirect Taiwan-Mainland China 
trade rose 39.55 percent. 
  Export orders from the United States and Japan increased 7.5 
percent and 3.67 percent, respectively, from the year-earlier 
levels. 
  Aggregate export orders placed with local manufacturers 
amounted to U.S.$29.09 billion in the first four months of this 
year, up 4.43 percent from the year before. 
  Economics Ministry officials said Taiwan's exports will 
gradually regain momentum in the coming months, judging from 
steady growth in export orders. 
  Exports grew a modest 2.3 percent in the January-April 
period, far lower than the originally targeted 7 percent growth. 
The lackluster export growth has prompted the government to 
adjust this year's economic growth target downward to 5.94 
percent from the previously-set 6.17 percent. 
  The officials attributed the slow export growth mainly to a 
rapid shrinking of labor-intensive industries here. For 
example, furniture, textile and footwear exports registered 
substantial declines during the four-month period. 
  The officials noted that as Taiwan has lost its competitive 
edge in such labor-intensive industries, the country should 
accelerate its development of capital and technology-intensive 
industries in order to maintain its niches in the world market. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

