<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Manufacturing Production Expected To Grow in 2d Quarter </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Manufacturing Production Expected To Grow in 2d Quarter </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2305090594 Taipei CNA in English 0719 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2305090594 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Danielle Yang] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 23 (CNA) -- Taiwan's manufacturing 
production is expected to post 5.41 percent growth for the 
second quarter of 1994, according to the Taiwan Institute of 
Economic Research. 
  The institute attributed the growth to rising foreign and 
overseas investment in Taiwan, strong export competitiveness, 
the economic recovery in the United States, and a depreciating 
NT [New Taiwan] dollar. 
  Rising investment can be seen from the 29 percent growth in 
foreign and overseas investments made in Taiwan during the first 
four months of this year. This is the first positive growth 
after two consecutive years of negative growth, and is an 
indication that foreign investors are gaining confidence in 
Taiwan's investment climate. 
  Brought up by rising interest rates and a recovering economy 
in the United States, the depreciating NT dollar is favorable 
for Taiwan's exports. Strong export trade also constitutes a 
factor in pushing up manufacturing production, the institute 
said. 

</TEXT>

