<H3> <TI>   Taipei To Help Southeast Asia Fight Dengue Fever </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Taipei To Help Southeast Asia Fight Dengue Fever </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2305085794 Taipei CNA in English 0723 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2305085794 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Danielle Yang] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 23 (CNA) -- Taiwan will share its 
experience in preventing dengue fever with Southeast Asian 
countries, Environmental Protection Administration Administrator 
Chang Lung-sheng said Monday [23 May]. 
  Chang made the remarks at the opening ceremony of an 
international dengue fever control meeting which gathered more 
than 180 experts and scholars from 19 countries in Taipei. 
  Chang said the main purpose for holding the meeting was to 
invite specialists to form a new dengue fever control alliance 
in Asia to jointly combat the disease and develop programs in 
urban areas to kill mosquitoes which carry the disease. 
  The meeting will also propose that a private foundation be 
established in Taiwan to help fight dengue fever, common in 
Southeast Asia and Mainland China, Chang said. 
  Taiwan eliminated dengue fever in just three years, Chang 
said, while neighboring Southeast Asian countries continue to 
fight the spread of the disease. 

</TEXT>

