<H3> <TI>   Official Says People's Rights `Should Be Protected' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Says People's Rights `Should Be Protected' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK2305103094 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in Chinese 0948 GMT 
19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK2305103094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Zhao Jian (6392 0256): "Chen Ziying Says All </F>
Hong Kong Residents' Legitimate Rights and Interests Should Be 
Protected"] 
  [Text] Beijing, 19 May (ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE)--Chen Ziying, 
deputy director of the State Council Hong Kong and Macao Affairs 
Office, said here today: All Hong Kong residents' legitimate 
rights and interests should be protected. 
  Chen Ziying made the above remarks when meeting with a 
delegation of British overseas Chinese community leaders led by 
Chiu Tien, chairman of the London Chinese Community Neighborhood 
Association. 
  Their ancestors came from Hong Kong's New Territories, and 
Chiu Tien and his party are very much concerned about Hong 
Kong's smooth transition. 
  Responding to the guests' worries, Chen Ziying said: Hong 
Kong's stability and prosperity is the most important concern 
during the transition period. After 1997, we will handle things 
in strict accordance with the Hong Kong Basic Law. He stressed: 
The principles of "one country, two systems" and "Hong Kong 
people ruling Hong Kong" will never be changed. 
  Chiu Tien and his party visited China at the invitation of 
the National People's Congress Overseas Chinese Affairs 
Committee. Some other noted figures in the overseas Chinese 
community in Britain also came, including Chen Chin-yu, Shan 
Sheng, Wen Liang-sheng, Huang Jung-fu, and Teng Han-sheng. 
Tomorrow, they will go to Sichuan to get an understanding of 
the investment environment there. 

</TEXT>

