<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Philippines' Ramos Supports Renewing MFN Status </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Philippines' Ramos Supports Renewing MFN Status </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2105111794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1051 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2105111794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Manila, May 21 (XINHUA) -- President Fidel Ramos 
today reiterated the Philippine Government's support for the 
continued grant by the United States of most-favored-nation 
(MFN) status to China without attached conditions. 
  U.S. President Bill Clinton has to decide whether to renew 
one more year China's MFN status by June 3 this year. 
  In reiterating his support for the MFN status of China, 
President Ramos said that a healthy relationship between China 
and the U.S., particularly in the area of trade, is good for the 
peace, stability and progress of the Asia-Pacific region. 
  He said linking politics to trade can only lead to both 
sides 
losing out, adding that grant of MFN status should also not be 
selective or qualified since this could be a source of more 
friction. 
  He stressed that the trade and economic issues should be 
divorced from political concerns and that the grant of MFN 
status should not subject to political conditionalities. 

</TEXT>

